name: db-dsc-s2gqx
title: Fsync vs No-Fsync Across Disk Types: HDD, Balanced SSD, SSD
description: Comparison: fsync-per-write vs no-fsync across three GKE persistent disk types (pd-standard HDD, pd-balanced, pd-ssd) — measures how disk hardware interacts with durability guarantees under sustained 60-second maximum-rate write bursts, with disk-level IOPS correlation

hypothesis.claim: Fsync latency is dominated by disk hardware — pd-ssd fsync should be 5-10x faster than pd-standard HDD, while no-fsync writes are uniformly fast regardless of disk type since they only hit the page cache
questions: How does fsync write latency vary across pd-standard, pd-balanced, and pd-ssd?
Is no-fsync latency truly independent of underlying disk type?
What is the sustained write throughput ceiling for each disk type under fsync?
Do node-level disk IOPS correlate with application-level fsync latency?
How does the fsync cost multiplier change across disk tiers?
focus: fsync latency distribution across disk types
sustained throughput ceiling per disk type
disk IOPS correlation with application latency
